# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: animal-liberation-victoria
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-cow-at-my-table] It covers the conflict between animal rights advocates and the meat industry, and their respective attempts to influence consumers.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-cow-at-my-table] It was directed, shot, and edited by Jennifer Abbott, who spent five years travelling across Canada, the United States, Australia and New Zealand to interview representatives on all sides.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-cow-at-my-table] The film intercuts these interviews with images of farm animals and industrial farming operations.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-cow-at-my-table] It explores what is sometimes popularly called factory farming.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-cow-at-my-table] The filming of *A Cow at My Table* drew early criticism from the Canadian meat industry, with both the Ontario Chicken Marketing Board and the Dairy Farmers of Ontario publishing articles warning of Abbott's actions.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-cow-at-my-table] Music for the film was performed by Oh Susanna.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Salt was active in a number of reform causes in the late 19th century, including prison reform, education, socialism, and animal protection.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He later founded the Humanitarian League in 1891.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] In *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays*, he argued that a vegetarian diet was humane, economical, and practicable, and challenged common objections to abstention from meat.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Across these essays, Salt defends vegetarianism on ethical, social, and economic grounds.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] He argues against the killing of animals for food, disputes the view that meat is necessary for health, and links diet to wider questions of conduct and social reform.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Several essays also attack blood sports and reply to objections made by critics of vegetarianism, including Sir Henry Thompson.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] Themes developed in *A Plea for Vegetarianism and Other Essays* appeared again in Salt's later writings, including *Animals' Rights: Considered in Relation to Social Progress* (1892).
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-plea-for-vegetarianism-and-other-essays] At a social meeting organised by the London Vegetarian Society on 20 November 1931, Gandhi said that Salt's *A Plea for Vegetarianism* had shown him that vegetarianism was "a moral duty" and not only a matter of custom or personal vow.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Robert Morris (1703–1754) was an English writer on architecture.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] His published works include *Lectures on Architecture* (1734–36), *An Essay on Harmony* (1739), and *The Art of Architecture* (1742).
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also wrote poems, essays, and pamphlets, and worked as a surveyor.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] According to Adams, Morris encountered *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood* in 1745.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Expecting an argument against flesh-eating, he instead found a defence of meat consumption based on a post-Flood reading of Genesis.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris disagreed with that interpretation and wrote a reply, which was published in 1746 as *A Reasonable Plea for the Animal Creation*.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] The treatise is made up of a preface, a letter to General Foliot, nine letters addressed to a friend, and a concluding reply to *A Dissertation on the Voluntary Eating of Blood*.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams writes that the central part of the book consists of letters Morris had written in 1737 and 1738 and later incorporated into the printed work.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Morris argues that humans have no natural right to kill animals for food.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He appeals both to Genesis and to "the nature and reason of things", maintaining that the food originally given to humans was the produce of the earth.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He rejects attempts to justify meat-eating through scripture, custom, bodily necessity, or animal predation.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] He also argues that humans are not naturally fitted for carnivory, and describes butchery and cookery as artificial practices rather than natural ones.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Drawing on writers such as Pythagoras and Plutarch, he attributes feeling and a degree of rationality to animals and treats their destruction for food as a matter of cruelty and injustice.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In her introduction to the 2005 republication, Carol J.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams describes the treatise as a neglected contribution to 18th-century vegetarian and animal-ethical writing.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She argues that Morris' case against flesh-eating is centred less on health than on moral obligation, and that his appeal to the "light of Nature" gives the work a distinctive place among early vegetarian texts.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Adams also comments on the book's epistolary form, noting that its letters are addressed to a flesh-eating friend.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She treats that structure as part of the book's argument, since Morris repeatedly answers objections and defends vegetarianism against the assumptions of a meat-eating society.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] She further notes Morris' rejection of claims of human superiority and his attribution of sentience and reason to animals.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] On Adams' reading, these features connect the treatise to later debates in animal ethics.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Before its republication in 2005, the treatise had appeared only occasionally in modern writing.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Whisker, John Simons, and Rod Preece each referred to it as an early contribution to vegetarian and animal-ethical thought.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Simons described Morris, together with John Hildrop, as a precursor to Humphry Primatt.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] Preece quoted from the treatise and placed Morris among earlier writers who argued for vegetarianism on ethical grounds, including John Oswald, George Nicholson, Joseph Ritson, and John Frank Newton.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-reasonable-plea-for-the-animal-creation] In 2005, the treatise was republished in *Organization & Environment* with an introductory article by Carol J.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Francis Hutcheson (1694–1746) was a philosopher of the Scottish Enlightenment and professor of moral philosophy at the University of Glasgow.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He was a leading defender of moral sense theory, according to which moral judgement arises from an innate sense rather than from reason alone.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He began work on *A System of Moral Philosophy* in 1738 and continued revising it until his death.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In *A System of Moral Philosophy*, Hutcheson sets out a broad account of ethics, natural law, private rights, and political society.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The first book concerns human nature and the supreme good.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses the faculties of the mind, the affections, and the will, and restates his view that human beings possess a moral sense by which they approve virtue and disapprove vice.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He argues that virtue is grounded in benevolence directed by reason, and relates moral life to providence and natural religion.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The second book deals with natural law and private rights.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson discusses obligation, contracts, property, promises, oaths, and legal duties.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He distinguishes between perfect and imperfect rights, and treats justice as distinct from broader duties of benevolence.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He also argues that laws should answer to reason, public good, and natural equity.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] The third book turns to civil society and government.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Hutcheson examines the basis of political authority, the forms of government, and topics including marriage, family, slavery, taxation, magistracy, war, and civil law.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] He holds that political power must be exercised for the common good and with the consent of the governed.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Modern commentators have drawn attention to Hutcheson's discussion of animals in the *System*.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] In a 2007 article, Aaron Garrett argued that Hutcheson offered an early argument for animal rights by grounding moral consideration in sentience and the capacity to suffer rather than in rational agency alone.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Garrett also compared Hutcheson's treatment of animals with his discussion of infants, and placed him in a line of thought distinct from Lockean rights theory.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Michael Bradie likewise noted that Hutcheson treated cruelty to animals as morally wrong because animals are capable of suffering.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] At the same time, Bradie argued that Hutcheson retained a hierarchical account in which human beings, because of their superior rational capacities, may use animals when necessary.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Bradie described this position as an early attempt to balance human interests with concern for animal suffering.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] Foulis in Glasgow and distributed in London by A.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] It appeared in two volumes in 1755, five years after Hutcheson's death; it was published posthumously by his son Francis Hutcheson the younger, from the original manuscript.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A new edition was published in 2000 by Thoemmes, with an introduction by Daniel Carey, and was later republished by A & C Black in 2006.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/a-system-of-moral-philosophy-in-three-books] A further edition was issued by Cambridge University Press in 2015.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abandoned-pets] Animal welfare laws in many states of the United States make it a crime to abandon a pet.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abandoned-pets] Often, when abandoned, pets are forced to fend for themselves and become stray or feral.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abandoned-pets] Feral cats are said to outnumber feral dogs and can become challenging to handle and socialize enough to be re-introduced to a new human owner.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abandoned-pets] In general, only some newly abandoned cats and very young feral kittens can be tamed.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abandoned-pets] There is a necessity to investigate interventions to prevent companion-animal relinquishment.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abandoned-pets] Stray animals increase potential exposure to zoonotic diseases like rabies.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abandoned-pets] Cat bites or scratches involving stray or feral animals are eight times more common than dog bites.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abandoned-pets] The impacts of dog and cat predation on wildlife can also be significant.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abandoned-pets] Some pets relinquished to an animal shelter will be euthanized due to a lack of space or financial resources.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abandoned-pets] Millions of companion animals enter animal shelters every year in the United States.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abandoned-pets] However, the number of dogs and cats euthanized in US shelters declined from approximately 2.6 million in 2011 to 1.5 million in 2018.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abandoned-pets] This decline can be partially explained by an increase in the percentage of animals adopted, and an increase in the number of stray animals successfully returned to their owners.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abandoned-pets] Studies show that the majority of people who relinquish an animal also report being emotionally attached to the animal.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abandoned-pets] It has been reported that when forced to abandon their animals in an evacuation, people suffer mental issues such as grief, depression, and post-traumatic stress disorder.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abandoned-pets] Recognizing the importance of pets to their owners and their role in public health is an essential first step in improving a public health problem that has been seen repeatedly in the past and is unlikely to change in the future.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abandoned-pets] Pet abandonment increased during the 2008 financial crisis.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abandoned-pets] In early 2009, the ASPCA published advice for people facing foreclosure and the loss of their pets, recommending finding a foster or adoption situation for your pet, being aware of rental property rules for pets, and checking with animal shelters and animal rescue groups.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] As the primary news division of the ABC, it is responsible for all news-gathering and coverage across the public broadcaster's various television, radio, and online platforms.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] ABC News has an extensive online presence which includes written news reports and videos, an ABC News mobile app (ABC Listen), podcasts, and in addition, all of the ABC News television programs available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment, and news in other languages.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] Simon Robinson was appointed director of the division on 28 May 2026.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] ABC News, from its inception in 1932, with ABC radio sourced its news from multiple sources, including cable news from London, its own bureaus in Europe, the Middle East and the Asia-Pacific, and in a fashion similar to commercial radio stations from local newspapers around Australia.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] Censorship was rife during the war, particularly after the U.S. entered the conflict on 7 December 1941.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] After General Douglas MacArthur set up his headquarters in Australia, he wielded enormous power, including on matters of censorship.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] Inter alia, he declared that every Australian radio station would only broadcast three news bulletins per day and that these would be simultaneous on all stations (ABC and commercial) at 7.45 a.m., midday, and 7.00 p.m.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] Weather forecasts were banned because it was felt that these may assist the enemy.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] The 7:45 a.m. bulletin was the only one that did not commence on the hour or the half-hour.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] It was placed at this timeslot as initially the ABC sourced its news from newspapers in a deal which required that news would not be broadcast earlier, to ensure newspapers sales were not affected.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] This bulletin continued at this time on ABC Local Radio stations until 19 September 2020, before being cancelled to save costs.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] Notices were issued banning radio stations from broadcasting some major wartime events, but as the federal government did not have the same power over the printed press as it did over the radio, newspapers usually reported events that radio was not permitted to mention.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] The ABC launched its first independent news bulletin on 1 June 1947 after years of negotiations with the Australian Government.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] The *Australian Broadcasting Corporation Act 1983* mandates that the ABC "shall develop and maintain an independent service for the broadcasting of news and information" both within Australia on a daily basis, and also to countries outside Australia.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] The name of the division and director responsible has changed over the years.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] In 2004 it was the News and Current Affairs Division when John Cameron took over as Director from Max Uechtritz as Director.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] The financial year 2008–2009 saw a lot of changes, both in the way that television content was produced as well as an "expansion of international news programming and continuous news across platforms, new programs and a range of appointments to senior positions".
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] Kate Torney became director of the News Division in April 2009.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] In November 2014, a cut of A$254 million to funding over the following five years meant that the ABC would have to shed about 10% of its total staff, around 400 people.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] There were several programming changes, with regional and local programming losing out to national programs, and the Adelaide TV production studio had to close apart from the news and current affairs section.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] In late 2015 Gaven Morris was appointed Director of the News Division.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] On 10 April 2017, ABC News introduced a new visual identity; as part of the changes, ABC News 24 and ABC NewsRadio were both rebranded as simply "ABC News", while their previously-separate social media presences were merged and unified under ABC News accounts.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] The Director's role changed its name to Director, News, Analysis & Investigations in 2017–2018, and as of June 2021 Morris was still in the role.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] During the 2017 to 2018 financial year, the ABC launched "Regional Connecting Communities" program, which provided funding for increased jobs in the regions, as well as more resources for local news, weather and live reporting.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] Justin Stevens was appointed director of the division of ABC News, Analysis and Investigations on 31 March 2022.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] Media executive and producer Kimberly Lynton "Kim" Williams AM was appointed chair of ABC News on 7 March 2024, with the term expected to conclude on 6 March 2029.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] In March 2026, staff at ABC began a one-day strike over pay and working conditions.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] This was the first walk out in 20 years.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] The division is responsible for all news-gathering and production of news output for ABC television, the ABC network of radio stations, and for its online services.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] In 2018 it was estimated that online ABC news and current affairs reached about 4.8 million users in Australia each month.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] As of 2021, the ABC News website includes ABC Sport, ABC Health, ABC Science, ABC Arts & Culture, ABC Fact Check, ABC Environment and news in other languages.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] The news theme used from the first days of ABC television from November 1956 to 1985 was "Majestic Fanfare", composed by Charles Williams.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] From 1956 until the early 1980s the version used was the abridged version performed by the Queen's Hall Light Orchestra, from a recording made in 1943.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] Each bulletin opened with a clip from the top story of the day, with the title "ABC News" superimposed over the footage.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] Later, this on-screen approach was replaced by a generic graphic title sequence.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] In 1982, to celebrate the ABC's 50th anniversary, a new version of the theme was commissioned, which incorporated both orchestral and new electronic elements.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] With the exception of a period in the mid-1980s, during which a synthesised theme ("Best Endeavours", written by Alan Hawkshaw, which was the theme for Channel 4 News in the UK) was used for around a year, this was used on radio until August 1988, and on television until early 1985.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] A reworking of "Majestic Fanfare" (essentially the original orchestration up one tone) was arranged by Richard Mills and recorded in 1988 by the Sydney Symphony Orchestra.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] From 1985, a theme composed by Tony Ansell and Peter Wall was used for 20 years, even after the 1998 brand refresh.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] In 2010, it was sampled and remixed by the group Pendulum and this revised work went on to be placed #11 on the Triple J Hottest 100 chart on Australia Day 2011.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] The theme for ABC News changed on Australia Day (26 January) 2005, to a piece written by Martin Armiger and John Gray, and for a couple of years it bore a resemblance to the original Peter Wall / Tony Ansell work in the opening signature notes.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] Wall challenged the ABC and was successful in reaching an agreement.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] The opening notes were removed and the work was re-arranged in 2010.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] The theme music from the 2005–2010 era was remixed by Armiger, giving it a more upbeat, synthesised feel.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] In August 2024, the Ansell–Wall theme was revived in an updated form as part of a larger rebranding of ABC News.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] The theme was remastered by David McDonald from the original multi-track studio recording, including a rerecorded piccolo, and layered samples of a children's drumkit (which McDonald had originally bought for his daughter) to add a bassier sound.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] On 4 March 1985, the ABC refreshed its structure and look, when the 7 o'clock news and the following current affairs program (at that time, *Nationwide*) were combined to form *The National*, and moved to 6:30 pm until 8 December 1985.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] After *The National* was deemed unsuccessful, On 9 December 1985, the news was refreshed again with a new set, graphics, and theme.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] In 1998, the set was updated, a new opener featuring a light blue globe and the ABC logo was introduced, and the theme remained the same but was tweaked.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] The graphics also changed to match the new look.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] On Australia Day (26 January) 2005, a new look (along with theme music) was introduced.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] The new look made use of an orange and blue globe motif.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] At the same time the set and graphics received a major overhaul to fit in with this look.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] This package was used until 21 July 2010, a day before the launch of ABC News.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] In January 2010, the ABC announced that a dedicated 24-hour digital television news channel, named ABC News 24 would be launched during the year.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] The new channel commenced preliminary broadcasting with a promo loop in early July 2010, with the ABC re-numbering ABC HD channel 20 to logical channel number 24.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] The channel was officially launched as ABC News 24 at 7:30 pm Australian Eastern Standard Time on 22 July 2010, and simulcast its first hour of transmission on ABC1.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] With the launch of ABC News on 22 July 2010, all 7 pm bulletins across Australia had a graphics overhaul to match the look of the new channel.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] The blue/orange globe style opener was replaced with a series of sliding panels, featuring images specific to each state.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] New sets were built in each capital city studio to match the ABC News 24 set and graphics were changed to match.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] The news bulletins such as *News Breakfast*, *ABC News Mornings*, *ABC News at Noon, ABC News Day,* *ABC News Afternoons*, *The World*, *ABC Late News* and *Weekend Breakfast* are aired on ABC News along with its own 30- and 15-minute hourly bulletins.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] National news updates are presented on ABC TV throughout the day, with evening updates at 7 pm presented live in most states by the respective state news presenters.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] Bulletins focus strongly on issues of state relevance, with a greater inclusion of national and international news items than are found in the news bulletins of commercial broadcasters.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] A national financial bulletin is presented on weeknights by Alan Kohler in Melbourne.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] The ABC's Ultimo studios produces the 8:30 pm weeknight update presented by Joe O'Brien.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] News and current affairs programs are also broadcast on ABC Australia, a channel broadcast to the region outside Australia.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] These include *Four Corners*, *7:30* and *Q+A*.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] ABC news television programs are available via the video-on-demand platform, ABC iview.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] ABC NewsRadio is a radio station dedicated to news and current affairs.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] It features national news bulletins at :00 and :30, with rolling news coverage during the remainder of each hour.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] In off-peak hours, it broadcasts content from partner providers such as the BBC World Service, NPR, and Deutsche Welle.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] Radio Australia, which covers the Asia-Pacific region, broadcasts regular bulletins produced in Melbourne, featuring reports from foreign correspondents in the region.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] State bulletins are produced by the ABC Local Radio station from the capital city of each state and mainland territory.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] They are broadcast to all ABC Local Radio and Radio National stations in each state, and focus strongly on issues of state relevance, but also feature national and international stories.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] National bulletins air when state bulletins are not produced.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] ABC Local Radio stations previously broadcast a flagship 15-minute state bulletin at 7:45 am, which in its final years was the only bulletin still introduced by the 18-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] All other bulletins were introduced by a 9-second version of Majestic Fanfare.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] This bulletin began in 1939 and was discontinued on Sunday 20 September 2020.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] ABC News produces several current affairs programs for radio.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] All share a quasi-magazine format, and investigate stories in greater depth compared to news bulletins.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] All ABC radio stations are available via an ABC News mobile app, ABC Listen, from which podcasts are also available.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] In March 2024, ABC News won the 2023 Gold Lizzie for Best Title at the IT Journalism Awards, a shared honour between ABC News Story Lab and ABC Radio.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abc-news-australia] ABC News also won Best Gaming Coverage and Best News Coverage.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists disagree on the strategy that must be used to achieve their goal.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists such as Steven Best and David Nibert argue, respectively, that embracing alliance politics and militant direct action for change (including civil disobedience, mass confrontation, etc), and transcending capitalism are integral to ending animal exploitation.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] Abolitionists generally oppose movements that seek to make animal use more humane or to abolish specific forms of animal use, since they believe this undermines the movement to abolish all forms of animal use.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] The objective is to secure a moral and legal paradigm shift, whereby animals are no longer regarded as things to be owned and used.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] The American philosopher Tom Regan writes that abolitionists want empty cages, not bigger ones.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] This is contrasted with animal welfare, which seeks incremental reform, and animal protectionism, which seeks to combine the first principles of abolitionism with an incremental approach, but which is regarded by some abolitionists as another form of welfarism or "New Welfarism".
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] The word relates to the historical term abolitionism—a social movement to end slavery or human ownership of other humans.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] Based on the way of evaluating welfare reforms, abolitionists can be either radical or pragmatic.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] While the former maintain that welfare reforms can only be dubiously described as moral improvements, the latter consider welfare reforms as moral improvements even when the conditions they permit are unjust.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] He calls such groups the "new welfarists", arguing that, though their aim is an end to animal use, the reforms they pursue are indistinguishable from reforms agreeable to traditional welfarists, who he says have no interest in abolishing animal use.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] He argues that reform campaigns entrench the property status of animals, and validate the view that animals simply need to be treated better.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] Instead, he writes, the public's view that animals can be used and consumed ought to be challenged.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] His position is that this should be done by promoting ethical veganism.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] Others think that this should be done by creating a public debate in society.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] He rhetorically asks, how can one hope to create some consumer base for this new vegan world when over a billion people live on less than a dollar a day?
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] Nibert acknowledges that post-capitalism on its own will not automatically end animal exploitation or bring about a more just world, but that it is a "necessary precondition" for such changes.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] New welfarists argue that there is no logical or practical contradiction between abolitionism and "welfarism".
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] Welfarists think that they can be working toward abolition, but by gradual steps, pragmatically taking into account what most people can be realistically persuaded to do in the short as well as the long term, and reduce animal suffering as it is most urgent to relieve.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] People for the Ethical Treatment of Animals, for example, in addition to promoting local improvements in the treatment of animals, promote vegetarianism.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] Although some people believe that changing the legal status of nonhuman sentient beings is a first step in abolishing ownership or mistreatment, others argue that this will not succeed if the consuming public has not already begun to reduce or eliminate its exploitation of animals for food.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 1992, Switzerland amended its constitution to recognize animals as *beings* and not *things*.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] The dignity of animals is also protected in Switzerland.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] New Zealand granted basic rights to five great ape species in 1999.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] Their use is now forbidden in research, testing or teaching.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] Germany added animal welfare in a 2002 amendment to its constitution, becoming the first European Union member to do so.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2007, the parliament of the Balearic Islands, an autonomous province of Spain, passed the world's first legislation granting legal rights to all great apes.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2013, India officially recognized dolphins as non-human persons.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2014, France revised the legal status of animals from movable property to sentient beings.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/abolitionism-animal-rights] In 2015, the province of Quebec in Canada adopted the Animal Welfare and Safety Act, which gave animals the legal status of "sentient beings with biological needs".
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] ALV was established in 1978 by Patty Mark, an animal rights activist.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] After reading Peter Singer's book Animal Liberation in 1978, Mark put a notice up in the local milk bar on 7 December 1978, that said ‘*Help the Hens’*, which attracted 17 people to Marks living room, initiating the beginning of ALV.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] In the early years of their operation, ALV’s activism was focused on improving animal welfare through liaising with the local department of agriculture, visiting abattoirs to prove that animals were stressed and therefore try and improve their living conditions.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] They also held street marches, outreach in shopping centers, school talks, and made petitions.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] In the late 1990’s, after reading the work of Gary L.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] Francine, Mark decided to change ALV from an animal welfare organisation, to an abolitionist animal rights organisation.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] In 1993, Mark received a call about the inhumane treatment of hens at a battery hen facility in Victoria, inspiring the birth of ALV's Open Rescue practice.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] Animal Liberation Victoria was the first group that made open rescues of hens.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] They have also protested against sheep exports, in Port of Devonport, whaling, the killing of animals on television by Jamie Oliver, animal deaths in Melbourne Zoo, and the 2007 Australian and New Zealand Council for the Care of Animals in Research and Teaching (ANZCCART) conference.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] In May 2005, they also offered to provide legal assistance to the students of a rural school, who opposed the idea to slaughter a pig and cow that they raised.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] Bernie Williams, executive producer of the 2016 film *Charlotte's Web*, wrote an e-mail to the school in support of the students.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] ALV educates the community about the horrors of animal agriculture with resources such as pig truth.com, cow truth.com, fishtruth.com and more.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] They educate the community about ethical alternatives to animal products with resources such as VeganEasy.org, and provide strategic support and development to the animal liberation movement.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] They also offer non-graphic presentations for schools across Victoria which highlight the relationship between human and non-human animals, and encourage students to think critically.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] They also perform video outreach on the streets of Australia, showing footage from investigations inside slaughterhouses to raise awareness for the animals who are suffering behind closed doors.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] Founded in 1986, Liberation Sanctuary is a registered non-profit charity and is Australia's longest running dedicated sanctuary for animals freed from the exploitation and slaughter inherent to animal agriculture.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] Liberation Sanctuary began after ALV founder Patty Mark, had several battery hens surrendered to her, and she looked after them at her large block of land, 10 kilometres from Melbourne’s CBD; Liberation Sanctuary’s first residence.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] This property became home to hundreds of animals over the next 30 years, with the local council providing Mark with a special animal permit that had conditions such as a limit to the number of animals on the property and no roosters or piglets, other than for short term care and rehabilitation.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] In 2016, Liberation Sanctuary moved to country Victoria on a 45 acre property which is now home to animals in need that have been taken in by ALV.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] Liberation Sanctuary vows to use their animal families’ freedom stories to educate the wider public on the importance of animal liberation and respect for all beings.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] Vegan Easy was founded in 2009 as an initiative of Animal Liberation Victoria.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] Since 2021, they have been partners with the charity, Vegan Australia.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] Vegan Easy is a grassroots campaign that promotes veganism as an ethical, rational, and earth friendly lifestyle.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] The campaign involves a 30 Day Challenge, which aims to support and motivate new vegans by showing them how easy and delicious vegan food can be.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] They also provide free resources including; basic nutrition advice, a health guide, eating out guide, vegan cheat sheet, and an ever growing collection of vegan recipes.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] The Ethical Community Program rewards people who donate $10 or more to ALV per month, with access to discounts from ethical, vegan businesses.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] On October 1, 2013, ALV held a public memorial at Melbourne's Federation Square, for the billions of land animals exploited and slaughtered every year.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] ALV activists held dead animals to draw the public’s attention to the way in which living beings seen as property suffer every day.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] In 2015, after anonymous footage was supplied to ALV through a whistleblower from a slaughterhouse in Laverton, ALV investigated three separate Victorian pig slaughterhouses; Diamond Valley Pork, Laverton; Australian Food Group, Laverton and C A Sinclair, Benella.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] They released footage of pigs being forced into metal cages with a high amperage electric prod, before being lowered into a gas chamber where the gas causes burning sensations throughout their bodies and they suffocate to death.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] To coincide with the release of the pig slaughter footage, ALV and other animal rights activists staged a non-violent, peaceful protest at the Victorian slaughterhouse, Diamond Valley Pork.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] Four activists chained themselves to the cages inside the slaughterhouse gas chamber and eight more, occupied the roof with banners, along with a larger group of around 50 protestors residing out the front.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] ALV founder Patty mark said that “activists involved in today’s action had taken a ‘vow of non-violence’ with an aim to close down the slaughterhouse for as long as possible.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] This action achieved extensive media coverage, and Diamond Valley Pork was successfully shut down for at least 3 hours due to the activists chaining themselves to the cages.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] They have had some conflicts with RSPCA Victoria.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] In March 2005, ALV found in the farm Parkhurst several injured, sick and dead hens.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] The police were called, and when they arrived and found the facts, Sergeant Mick Brien phoned the RSPCA for assistance, who refused to attend.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] Then the police arranged for ALV to remove the sick and dying hens and escorted them to Werribee Vet Clinic.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] Patty Mark, ALV president, said "Unfortunately the RSPCA not only refused to attend and assist the police on the night, they have failed to do an urgent inspection this morning taking other very ill and dehydrated birds to a vet or to even contact the owner.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] They only told ALV they would look at the place "next week" and "If the police and members of ALV can see the suffering and know it is wrong and illegal, why can't the RSPCA?
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] Once again they have failed in their duty to protect "all creatures great and small", and it is time they were made accountable".
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] RSPCA Chief Executive Officer, Maria Mercurio, responded to Mark, insinuating that they would not be following in the footsteps of the RSPCA UK’s decision, instead they stated that “a vegan or vegetarian lifestyle is not what the RSPCA is all about.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] However, at all of our events where food is served, vegetarian options are always presented”.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] "We know that ALV will continue to attend RSPCA events in Victoria and target our staff, volunteers and guests.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] ALV has also criticised that while the RSPCA says it's against battery cages, they are in business with the largest battery egg producer in Australia, Pace Farms.
[src:animal-liberation-victoria/animal-liberation-victoria] They have also accused RSPCA approved barnlaid sheds of which ALV claim to have documented later "overcrowding, beak mutilations, lack of perches, prevention of roosting, chronic stress and electric shock training to the hens", among many other criticisms.
